<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 94 / Highland bags 10% rise midway with help of Famous Grouse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Highland Distilleries, the Scotch whisky producer, has bucked the trend of
falling profits in the whisky industry with a 10 per cent increase in
pre-tax profits to Pounds 23.4m in the six months to February and a 10 per
cent dividend rise.
Mr John Goodwin, chairman, said the rise in operating profit - up 2 per cent
to Pounds 13.6m - was attributable to the performance of the Famous Grouse
brand, which now provides some 45 per cent of group profit before tax.
In the UK, Grouse volume was slightly down, but market share was maintained.
Market share in Scotland dipped from 24 to 23 per cent, but rose from 11 to
12 per cent in England and Wales, leaving the UK share unchanged at 14 per
cent.
Highland said the UK price of Grouse was constant, while competitors' prices
had fallen. Mr Goodwin said: 'We could easily increase our volume through
promotional support and lower prices, but that would do a lot of damage. Our
premium price position is of vital importance.'
Exports of Famous Grouse, accounting for 40 per cent of the brand, were up
16 per cent by volume and 30 per cent by value. Mr Goodwin said that whereas
three years ago exports accounted for only 20 per cent of the total and made
no contribution to profit, they had moved steadily into profit since then.
The combination of falling sales at home and rising sales abroad meant that
overall volume had held steady.
Sales of new whisky fillings were down 20 per cent. However, orders for
calendar 1994 were up 9 per cent. Sales of mature malt whiskies were up, and
volume sales of the Highland Park malt brand were up 23 per cent.
Capacity utilisation at the group's distilleries was slightly better at just
over 40 per cent.
Mr Goodwin said it was difficult to see any change in the overall market in
the course of 1994, although he expected a 'fairly modest' turnround in
1995.
Interest receivable rose from Pounds 2.1m to Pounds 3.2m, with the net cash
position moving from a negative Pounds 2.8m to a positive Pounds 14.7m.
Income from associates - mostly the related whisky company Robertson &amp;
Baxter - was Pounds 6.6m (Pounds 5.8m), with much of the increase
attributable to the first-time consolidation of the North British grain
distillery.
Earnings per share were up 9 per cent at 12.2p (11.2p). The interim dividend
has been raised to 1.76p (1.6p).
</TEXT>
