<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 94 / The Lex Column: Amec
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Given that at the interim stage the City expected Amec to make Pounds 30m in
1993, a full year profit of Pounds 21m is a real disappointment. That is
especially true because the company looks unlikely to beat the Pounds 30m
target this year, despite the gathering improvement in the UK housing
market. The result only underlines how far market enthusiasm for cyclical
stocks exceeded their capacity to deliver. Not only are contracting profits
much further out in the economic cycle; the tax charges for companies which
have run up losses in the recent past will rise as recovery comes. Earnings
performance may well be pedestrian over the next two or three years.
With contracting remaining difficult it is odd that Amec's shares are
trading at a premium to pure UK housebuilders. They are more obvious early
beneficiaries of low interest rates and economic recovery. Construction
companies also generate uncertainty because timing of profits over long
contracts makes profits hard to model. The sector as a whole might benefit
from an accelerated trend towards greater disclosure. A more detailed
breakdown of Amec's North Sea and mechanical engineering businesses might
help reassure.
Even so, as Amec points out, excess capacity in construction is likely to
dog the industry for some time, making positive surprises even less likely.
Shareholders might have greater justification for the last year's enthusiasm
if the shares had managed more than a 2 per cent annual compound capital
growth rate over the last decade.
</TEXT>
