<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 94 / Arts: Clean Break's Red
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MALCOLM RUTHERFORD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Anna Reynolds, the writer in residence for the Clean Break Theatre Company,
has developed an unmistakeable style.
Clean Break means what its name suggests, plus a lacing of feminism: it is a
company for women ex-prisoners and ex-offenders wishing to break with the
past.
Ms Reynolds was once a prisoner. Her writing draws heavily on her experience
and suggests that she sees theatre as a kind of therapy for those who are
locked up, though I suspect that no one can write as well as she does
without considerable background reading. In any case, her works are already
appealing to a wider audience, and deservedly so.
Her early piece, Jordan, was first performed at the Lilian Baylis Theatre
two years ago. The revival of that acclaimed production can still just about
be caught (that is, until April 10) at the Battersea Arts.
Based on a true story about a woman, Shirley Jones, who was incarcerated for
killing her baby son and then committed suicide on the day of her release
from prison, it is a monologue full of incident. As in the original, it is
superbly acted by Moira Buffini, the co-author, as Shirley.
Ms Reynolds's Wild Things was enthusiastically reviewed by my colleague,
Alastair Macaulay, when it had its premiere in Salisbury last November. It
is now touring.
The new work is Red at the New End Theatre in Hampstead. The trouble is that
the author has already set such high standards that the immediate comment is
that Red is not quite as good as Jordan. There is the slight feeling of
having been there before.
In Red there are two characters, both of them women in a remand cell beneath
a Crown court and both of them charged with a murder of a kind. This may
seem an advance on Jordan in that there is an opportunity for dialogue as
well as narrative. There are certainly contrasts.
One of the women, Gerda, is white English upper middle class, aged 40. She
has not directly murdered her husband, but has not exactly discouraged her
rough young lover from doing so.
If you note a borrowing from Hester in Terence Rattigan's The Deep Blue Sea,
you will not be alone. Gerda prefers sex to respectability. She is
immaculately played by Carrie Thomas, who keeps her make-up in place to the
last.
Gerda is also socially adept. Kay, her companion in the prison cell, is
black. When Gerda asks her where she comes from, there is only momentary
surprise when the answer is Essex, not somewhere in the Caribbean. Gerda
takes it in her stride.
Kay, played very strongly by Leonora Rogers-Wright, is more skilled in the
ways of dealing with judges and juries. She has picked up some of the lines
from Shirley Jones in Jordan: when to smile at the bench, when to cry and
when not and when to try to tell the truth.
The women talk to each other, or at each other, a lot. They recognise that
they are more or less in the same boat: social and ethnic differences are
irrelevant.
But there is no great dialogue, and in the end I concluded that there was
more variety in the monologue of Shirley Jones. Still, Ms Reynolds can
certainly write. Red, like Jordan, is directed by Fiona Buffini, sister of
Moira.
Continuing at the New End, Hampstead, until April 24. 071 794 0022.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7922 Theatrical Producers and Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
