</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A chief executive who has demonstrated considerable flair in the running of
his own Tec has been appointed as the first full-time director of policy and
strategy for the 82 Tecs in England and Wales.
Chris Humphries, who has been chief executive of Hertfordshire Tec since
1991, is expected to take up the position in June. In effect he will be
chief executive of the Tec secretariat which supports the work of the Tec
National Council, a body which represents Tecs nationally, in particular in
their relationship to the government.
Responsibility at a national level for policy and strategy has until now
been handled in a part-time capacity by Richard Guy, the chief executive of
South and East Cheshire Tec and Business Link.
Humphries, 44, is expected to play a key role in negotiations between Tecs
and the government as well as interfacing between the several specialist
committees that develop Tecs' policies. He will report to Mike Bett, the
former deputy chairman of British Telecom, who has taken over as
non-executive chairman of the Tec national council in succession to Edward
Roberts.
