FT  08 APR 94 / Lottery criminal checks planned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The National Lottery Office has found that a number of directors of
companies associated with bids to run the UK's national lottery have
criminal convictions that they failed to disclose, Raymond Snoddy writes.
All eight bidders yesterday received letters saying that some people had not
made the full and detailed disclosure required.
Mr Peter Davis, director-general of the lottery, who is expected to announce
the winner of the licence next month, has stressed the importance of probity
in all aspects of the lottery. Yesterday's letters do not specify which bids
involved directors with apparently undeclared convictions.
The lottery has asked all bidders for permission to approach all those
involved so that the information it has can be 'confirmed or negated'.
The lottery, to be launched late this year or early next, is designed to
raise money for five 'good causes' in equal proportion - the arts,
charities, a millennium fund, the national heritage and sport.
