<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 94 / Patten's warm reception fails to thaw Malaysian freeze:
Optimism on educational links has done little to improve the trade outlook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KIERAN COOKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Patten, the education secretary, this week became the first cabinet
minister to visit Malaysia since Dr Mahathir Mohamad, the country's prime
minister, announced a ban on British companies winning government contracts.
But his visit - to discuss expanding the already considerable educational
links between Britain and Malaysia - has not marked any relaxation of the
ban, imposed more than six weeks ago, in retaliation for unfavourable
reports in the Britsh press about Dr Mahathir and Malaysia.
British companies are failing to be shortlisted for contracts and face the
break-up of partnerships with local and other businesses.
The most serious blow has been to companies involved in a Pounds 2bn-plus
project to build an international airport outside Kuala Lumpur. Ajac, a
consortium of BICC, GEC-Marconi, Gammon and Trafalgar House of Britain and
Marubeni of Japan, carried out initial planning and won the design and
engineering contract for the airport.
The Malaysian works ministry has now disclosed that it is vetting 29
pre-qualification applications to bid for the airport's construction and
none of them is British.
John Laing had put in a preliminary tender for a MDollars 3bn (Pounds 753m)
terminal at the airport. It is believed to have withdrawn after its local
and foreign partners expressed fears that its inclusion could jeopardise
their chances.
The National Grid company was to have participated in a MDollars 1.6bn
project to install power transmission lines for Tenaga Nasional, Malaysia's
semi-privatised electricity utility. Pressure from local partners is likely
to result in National Grid withdrawing.
Some companies have decided to carry on regardless. Up to 90 British
defence-related companies are due at an exhibition in Kuala Lumpur this
month even though the Malaysian defence minister has said there will be no
more purchases of arms and equipment from Britain.
A group of British oil industry experts recently gave a seminar to Petronas,
the Malaysian state oil company. Soon afterwards Petronas announced that
British companies would be excluded from future contracts in Malaysia.
One British executive based in Malaysia said: 'The longer it goes on, the
worse it gets. It seems we are just laying down and being kicked.'
Other companies are aware of the opportunities. Britain had hoped for a
share of a MDollars 4bn programme to equip the Royal Malaysian Navy with new
patrol vessels. During the past 10 days delegations from France and Sweden
have been suggesting collaborative work on the vessels. Similar delegations
are due from Germany and Australia.
Mr Patten said he had been 'heartened by the warmth of my reception'. He
added: 'There is an extraordinary atmosphere of friendliness.' He will take
an optimistic message back to London on the educational front, where
Malaysia needs British assistance.
But this week Dr Mahathir repeated that the British press must stop telling
'lies'. He added: 'We will not change our policy as long as this campaign
goes on. We will wait and see. We have plenty of time.'
The outlook for British companies remains grim.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    MYZ  Malaysia, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
