<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 94 / Bidders attracted to Scots pits sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two companies yesterday announced the formation of a joint venture to bid
for the Scottish region of British Coal in a move which strengthens the
industry's belief that the corporation's assets north of the border may be
its most attractive.
Miller Group, a construction and mining company, and Ryan Group, a coal
producer, said their company Scotcoal would bid formally for the Scottish
region after publication in June by the government of information on British
Coal.
Several other companies have formed a consortium, Mining (Scotland), also
with the intention of making a bid. Mr David Cawthra, Miller chief
executive, said both Miller and Ryan saw Scotland as the main opportunity in
the privatisation of British Coal.
Mr Crispian Hotson, Ryan chief executive, said that unlike other areas of
the UK, demand for coal in Scot-land was growing, from 4.5m tonnes this year
to an estimated 7.5m in 1998. This was partly because of the strengthening
of the electricity interconnector between England and Scotland which will
enable the Scottish power companies to export south of the border.
Mr Hotson said he was also interested in Scottish coal because of its low
sulphur content and the extensive reserves at Longannet, the country's last
deep mine in operation.
Longannet produces coal at about Pounds 1.40 a gigajoule, the joint venture
estimates, against sale prices in contracts with Scottish Power and
Hydro-Electric of Pounds 1.50 falling to Pounds 1.30 in four years.
Ryan is also considering a bid for British Coal's north-east region in
association with Alcan, the north American aluminium company.
Mr Cawthra said Ryan and Miller had assets of about Pounds 100m. The two
companies currently mine more than 2.5m tonnes of coal a year in Scotland,
representing more than 40 per cent of British Coal's Scottish production.
The Scottish region is one of five being sold. Sales are expected to be
effected by early next year.
Greener valleys, Page 16
</TEXT>
