<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 94 / World Trade News: Free trade plans in pipeline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A list of countries which the Clinton administration considers eligible for
free trade agreements with the US will be presented to Congress in the
summer.
Mr Jeffrey Garten, Commerce Department undersecretary, said yesterday that a
country's eligibility would depend on factors such as economic reform,
openness to imports, and protection for intellectual property rights.
He drew distinctions between such countries and those suitable to join the
North American Free Trade Agreement - requiring approval by both Canada and
Mexico. Chile's prospects were brightest, he said, and Argentina 'will merit
consideration in the very near future'.
On a recent trip to Latin America, Mr Garten stressed that free trade
throughout the Americas was still the Administration's ultimate goal. In the
meantime, the US was committed to a process of integration which was as
inclusive as possible, transparent - 'to encourage reformers' - and designed
to open trade, not to create exclusive blocs.
</TEXT>
