<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 94 / New editor for New York Times
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Joseph Lelyveld, managing editor of the New York Times and a
distinguished former foreign correspondent, is to become executive editor of
the paper on July 1, in succession to Mr Max Frankel, who is stepping down
after eight years in the post, writes Martin Dickson in New York.
Mr Lelyveld, who is 57, had long been regarded as front runner to succeed
64-year-old Mr Frankel.
He has been managing editor since 1990, was foreign editor of the paper from
1987 to 1989 and had held many overseas reporting posts, including two
spells in South Africa.
He won a Pulitzer Prize in 1986 for 'Move Your Shadow', a book illustrating
the impact of apartheid on South African society.
He will be succeeded as managing editor by Mr Eugene Roberts, 61, a former
NYT employee, who was editor of the Philadelphia Inquirer for 18 years and
is now a professor at the University of Maryland's college of journalism. Mr
Frankel will become a columnist for the NYT magazine, writing about
communications and the media.
</TEXT>
