<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 94 / Challenge to union candidate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Rival factions in Spain's General Workers' Union (UGT), the Socialist labour
confederation, yesterday joined battle over a new leadership, at a time when
the union's fortunes and its relations with the Socialist government are at
a low ebb. A little-known unionist from Andalucia, Mr Candido Mendez,
appeared well placed to take over the leadership at the end of the union's
four-day congress on Sunday, as the chosen successor of the veteran Mr
Nicolas Redondo. However, Mr Mendez faces a challenge from the more
combative Mr Manuel Fernandez, head of the UGT's powerful metalworkers'
federation, who is strongly supported in the industrial and mining regions
of northern Spain.
</TEXT>
