<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Italy's Northern League and the neo-fascist National Alliance - members of
the right-wing alliance which won last week's election - held a surprise
meeting yesterday to discuss federalism, the principal issue which divides
them. Senior League politicians said Mr Umberto Bossi, leader of the
federalist League, and Mr Gianfranco Fini, secretary of the National
Alliance, had not talked about the post-election political crisis. Earlier
this week, Mr Silvio Berlusconi, leader of Forza Italia, the third member of
the victorious pact, suspended talks with his allies on forming a government
after seven days of squabbling. He will wait for Italy's president to name a
prime minister later this month before renewing negotiations.
The League said yesterday's meeting was a positive step, if only because the
National Alliance - which favours a more centralised state  - had agreed to
discuss federalism. Mr Fini, however, said federalism was only acceptable as
part of a presidential regime.
