<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 94 / Barclaycard offers rebates to win business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Barclaycard is offering rebates of up to Pounds 150 to credit card holders
who transfer outstanding debts from other cards.
The move by Britain's largest credit card issuer illustrates the
increasingly fierce competition in the market. Barclaycard already accounts
for one-third of the 27m cards in issue in the UK.
Previously, only smaller credit card issuers - especially those trying to
break into the UK market - have offered rebates or lower interest rates on
balances transferred from another card.
Competition in the card market - where spending through credit and debit
cards totalled almost Pounds 50bn in 1993 - stepped up noticeably last
autumn when Vauxhall Motors, a subsidiary of General Motors, launched a
British version of the GM card available in the US. Just over 300,000 GM
Visa and Mastercards have been issued so far in the UK.
Ford then joined forces with Barclaycard to issue a branded card, in what
was seen as a direct response to the GM card. It became available from the
beginning of this month.
Only yesterday, another non-traditional competitor entered the market when
Texaco, the oil company, announced it would be issuing a Visa card jointly
with the Bank of Scotland.
In addition to the new entrants, financial institutions such as Save &amp;
Prosper have been trying to expand their existing small customer bases by
offering lower interest rates. Clearing bank issuers such as Barclaycard
have also lost some business to cards which do not charge an annual fee.
Barclaycard's rebate offer, promoted this week in a press advertising
campaign, credits a new or existing customer who transfers a balance from
another card with 5 per cent of the outstanding balance. The maximum rebate
is Pounds 150, which would be paid on transferred balances of Pounds 3,000
or more.
Mr Richard Reay-Smith, Barclaycard chief executive, said the cost of the
offer was not being subsidised by existing card holders, since it came from
within the recruitment budget. Cross-subsidy - the so-called 'free ride'
received by customers who pay off their bills each month - was one of the
factors cited by banks when they introduced annual fees.
The new Texaco Global Visa card will carry no annual fee for the first year.
In subsequent years the Pounds 10 charge will be waived if annual spending
exceeds Pounds 2,000. The Texaco card's annualised percentage rate of 20.5
per cent is in the lowest quartile for credit card interest rates.
Like many cards, including Barclaycard, the Texaco card will have an
incentive scheme based on the amount spent. Its use at a Texaco service
station will earn double points.
Mr Reay-Smith said Barclaycard had no plans to waive its annual fee of
Pounds 10, regardless of how much the card was used. He added Barclaycard
was not intending to reduce the APR of 20.7 per cent (or 21.9 per cent on
average spending when the annual fee is taken into account).
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
