<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 94 / Output rise signals strong recovery: Figures suggest
broad-based revival - Production growth brings inflation warning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The recovery in British industry strengthened decisively in February, as
robust manufacturing growth helped push overall production back above its
pre-recession levels.
The index of industrial production - which covers manufacturing and the
energy and water sectors - rose to 100.7 in February, its highest level
since a 102.1 peak in June 1990. In the three months to February the index
was 0.6 per cent higher than in the previous three months, and up 3.7 per
cent compared with the same period a year ago.
Buoyed by healthy performances from the engineering and food sectors,
manufacturing output rose a seasonally adjusted 0.6 per cent on the month,
well ahead of market expectations for a 0.4 per cent rise. This followed
January's increase of 1 per cent.
In the three months to February, output rose 0.8 per cent against the
previous three months, to stand 2 per cent up on the same period a year ago.
Signs of a clear revival in industry will hearten the government as new
taxes on individuals - most of them effective this month - threaten to slow
consumer spending, currently the strongest element of the economy.
The Treasury said yesterday's figures were 'entirely consistent' with
recovery across a broad front, and that it was particularly encouraged by a
pick-up in output of goods used for industrial investment.
According to calculations by the Central Statistical Office, manufacturing
output is now rising at an annualised rate of about 3 per cent.
But yesterday's news of accelerating output was accompanied by a warning on
inflation. A report from Income Data Services, a research company, said the
majority of pay rises this year were ahead of the current inflation rate of
2.4 per cent.
IDS said that 'a modest upward shift in pay settlements has been under way
since the start of the year' with some firms paying higher bonuses and
offering more overtime to staff.
On the London stock market, dealers took the view that the manufacturing
output figures reduced the chances for a further cut in interest rates.
However, a 2.5-point drop in the FT-SE 100 share index to 3,129.0 yesterday
reflected a general weakness in the US stock market rather than fears that
UK lending rates have reached their low point.
According to the figures, much of the recent strength in manufacturing is
due to higher output of investment goods rather than consumer goods.
Investment goods output rose 1.1 per cent in February after a 4.1 per cent
increase in January. In the three months to the end of February, it was 1.8
per cent up on the previous three months, boosted mainly by a sharp rise in
the output of electrical goods.
By contrast, consumer goods output rose 0.4 per cent in February, after a
0.1 per cent increase in January. It was up 0.6 per cent in the latest three
months, with a drop in car production offset by rises in output elsewhere.
Analysts said the official figures finally confirmed the optimism of recent
industrial trends surveys by the Confederation of British Industry and
others.
Details, Page 6
Sharp rise in housebuilding starts welcomed, Page 6
Lex, Page 18
