<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / Survey of Danish Banking and Finance (4): Points scored -
Jyske Bank discloses more than expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HILARY BARNES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Jyske Bank, the Jutland-based bank which ranks as the country's fourth
largest with assets of about DKr56bn, has long enjoyed the role of
provocateur, never losing an opportunity to score verbal points off the big
Copenhagen-based banks.
It has done it again this year. It has defied the recommendations of the
Bankers' Association and the Finance Supervisory Authority by disclosing
much more information about the bank in its 1993 annual report than the
supervisors recommend or other banks disclose.
Jyske's action has not met with universal acclaim, and some of the wind was
taken out of its sails by Unidanmark, which when it launched its
international equity issue in February had to disclose more information in
the prospectus than would have been required by an issue directed at
domestic investors).
There was just a touch of sour grapes in the comment from a senior manager
at Den Danske Bank, who pointed out that much more extensive disclosure
practices by the Swedish banks had not helped either them or their investors
to foresee the difficulties which the Swedish banks met in 1991-92.
The problem is not so much a general desire to restrict disclosure, however,
as the argument that the banks should first agree on what to disclose and to
ensure that the criteria for the information disclosed means that like can
be safely compared with like.
The problem is a long-standing one, and the Bankers'Association and the
Supervisory Authority are still working towards acceptable definitions and
standards.
Information which is not normally disclosed by Danish banks includes the
size of non-performing loans, the size of the contingency reserve (the sum
of past loss provisions after deduction of realised losses), lending by
business sectors, and a detailed analysis of credit policy and market risks
arising from changes in interest rates, foreign exchange gyrations, share
price movements, and liquidity risks.
'I'm blowed if I can see why we shouldn't tell our own shareholders and
customers as much as Unibank has to tell foreign investors,' said Jyske's
chief executive, Mr Kaj Steenkjaer, when he presented his bank's 1993 annual
report at the bank's headquarters in the mid-Jutland town of Silkeborg.
The report contains all the above information and more and he received an
accolade on the same occasion from the bank's biggest shareholder, the
representative of the ATP National Labour Market Pension Fund, for its
efforts to improve the transparency and informative value of its own
accounts.
Jyske demonstrated the courage of its convictions by increasing disclosure
at a time when it is still carrying heavy loss provisions, rather than
waiting for a year when everything looked wonderful.
Like all the banks, the bottom line improved last year. Jyske made a profit
of DKr429m compared with a 1992 loss of DKr919m. Loss provisions were cut to
DKr844m from DKr1.26bn in 1992, while realised and unrealised gains on
securities added Dkr708m to 1993 profits against a loss of DKr7m in 1992.
The bank's capital adequacy ratio is strong, with tier one capital at 8.1
per cent of risk-weighted assets and its total capital adequacy ratio at
10.9 per cent.
But non-performing credits, which were under one per cent of loans and
guarantees in 1989, climbed to 4.10 per cent from 3.4 per cent in 1992.
Loss provisions were still a relatively high 2.2 per cent of loans and
guarantees, though down from a peak of 3.1 per cent in 1992. We also now
know that Jyske Bank always has DKR2bn in liquid assets on hand to meet
day-to-day needs, or about five per cent of deposits.
At the end of last year it had liquid assets on hand to cover a period of 12
weeks in a worst-case situation, when no deposits were renewed. The message
seems to be clear: there's no need to rush.
</TEXT>
