<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / London Stock Exchange: ICI recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, JOEL KIBAZO, PETER JOHN and CHRISTINE BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in ICI recovered from recent weakness, improving 16 to 802p, as some
of the gloomier analysts appeared to be taking a more benign view of the
company.
Hoare Govett, a former company broker which has been consistently bearish,
argued that stabilisation in mainland Europe and a firmer base to the sector
might render ICI slightly more attractive.
Although he stressed he was not yet changing his stance, Mr Martin Evans of
Hoare said: 'Given anecdotal comments from the European chemical industry. .
. (ICI could) . . . surprise both internal and external observers by the
magnitude and momentum of the response to better trading conditions.'
Encouragement from a strong overnight performance on Wall Street fuelled
interest in the high profile debut of House of Fraser. The confidence that
fed into the UK market from New York encouraged institutions to take larger
positions in the new stock.
The shares closed at a premium of 6 1/2 to their issue price of 180p and
turnover of 22m shares was the second heaviest in London.
However, the initial performance of the largest flotation this year did no
more than match market expectations considering the favourable trading
conditions. And some analysts were slightly disappointed at the volume
traded.
Much of the business was conducted by SG Warburg, the company broker, and
most of the buying came from UK institutions.
Anticipation that Boots would sell its pharmaceutical division prompted
active trading in the stock. Interest was sharpened by Boots' appointment of
Credit Suisse to handle a future unbundling of the drugs arm. UBS was a keen
buyer of the stock. The shares added 12 at 519p in a turnover of 3.5m.
Confirmation by Associated British Foods that it was in talks to sell its
Baker's Oven chain of bakery outlets to Greggs pushed the AB Foods shares up
6 to 583p in thin turnover. Greggs was unchanged at 743p.
International conglomerate Hanson slipped 4 to 265p, with one US brokerage
said to have been an active seller.
Pharmaceutical group Glaxo improved 12 to 618p after recent underperformance
as the shares responded to earlier strength on Wall Street and the company
confirmed that Serevent, its anti-asthma treatment, went on sale in the US.
Media and leisure conglomerate Pearson languished after one investor sold a
block of 1.8m shares at 621p, well below the market price.
Analysts said the shares had outperformed the FT-SE-Actuaries All-Share
Index by more than 40 per cent over the past year in spite of recent falls,
and investors had used last week's purchase of Software Toolworks as an
opportunity to take profits.
Pearson closed 7 easier at 631p with 5.2m shares traded, unusually high for
the stock.
The oil sector passed what one specialist described as its first real
post-Opec test, with most oil issues moving ahead strongly after a resilient
performance by crude oil prices, which held comfortably above the Dollars 14
a barrel level.
Oil major British Petroleum rose 7 to 357p on turnover of 14m amid talk of
good US demand, while Shell Transport, after Hoare Govett reaffirmed its
positive stance on the stock, gained 9 at 671p.
Lasmo continued recent good performance, the shares adding 5 at 129p on 10m
dealt, after support from the UK and US.
Retail bank National Westminster, the worst performer in the FT-SE 100
relative to the FT-SE-Actuaries All-Share Index during the last quarter,
improved 7 to 476p amid talk of substantial switching out of Barclays. The
latter settled 3 firmer at 536p.
SG Warburg spearheaded a general advance by the merchant banks, closing 21
ahead at 778p, helped by the rally in markets in recent sessions.
Engineering group GKN put on 14 at 555p after Kleinwort Benson turned
positive on the stock. Several other brokers also bought the stock on a view
that the acquisition of Westland Group will enhance earnings.
Volume in aerospace and motor components group Lucas Industries jumped to
8.1m and the shares moved 4 ahead to 193p after Credit Lyonnais Laing
reiterated its buy recommendation. The broker was also a buyer of British
Steel -  3/4 up at 141 3/4 p on turnover of 9.3m - following a visit to the
company.
Hard hit Fisons rose 3 to 132p with the help of a buy recommendation from
BZW.
Bid speculation returned to Brent International as the shares gained 3 at
118 1/2 p. The improvement marked a 20 per cent rise in the troubled
chemical company's share price since its low just after announcing a reduced
dividend and profits in early March.
Good results off the field for Manchester United made up for recently lost
ground. The shares rallied 15 to 675p.
Hotel group City Centre added 3 at 82p on well-received figures.
Elsewhere, Stakis was heavily traded as nil-paid stock from the recent
rights issue came on to the market. There were rumours that the Stakis
family had unloaded large blocks of equity, with one lump of 5.6m shares
said to have been placed at 80 1/4 p. The ordinary shares finished the day
firmer at 80 1/2 p in volume of 6.5m. Turnover in the nil-paid soared to
20m, with the price adding  1/2 at 8 1/2 p.
Channel tunnel operator Eurotunnel bounced 4 to 509p as market watchers
pondered the implications of a reported tussle over certain aspects of the
underwriting of its impending rights issue.
