<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / World Stock Markets: Argentina lives through trial by fire
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BARHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Argentina has been one of the worst performing Latin American equity markets
so far this year, living through its first trial by fire in international
financial markets since making the currency convertible, and adopting a
fixed exchange rate three years ago.
In March, when the central bank spent a record Dollars 725m - 5 per cent of
its reserves - to defend the peso, the Merval share index fell 16 per cent.
This week the Merval index has remained volatile in line with international
markets, losing some 8.5 per cent on Monday but recouping 4 per cent the
following day.
The unrest in international markets has demonstrated the fragility of
funding for Argentina's 1994 external deficits, forecast at Dollars 10bn to
Dollars 12bn. Recently low international interest rates, and strong demand
for private company debt issues, may not bridge this gap painlessly.
The turmoil has underlined the precariousness of regulation with brokerages
not closely supervised. Analysts believe that trading losses will wipe out
first-quarter earnings at listed banks such as Banco Galicia and Banco
Frances.
The recent sacking of Mr Martin Redrado as president of the independent CNV
securities commission accentuated another troubling feature. He questioned
terms under which the government negotiated with US investment banks Merrill
Lynch and CS First Boston to sell shares worth Dollars 720m held by
pensioners in privatised oil group YPF.
