<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / Markets Report: Dollar rally continues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A fairly small cut in the German repo rate yesterday helped the dollar and
sterling maintain a firmer tone on foreign exchanges, writes Philip Gawith.
The US currency was also helped by a story in the Washington Post newspaper
saying that the Federal Reserve was unlikely to change short-term interest
rates until financial markets had calmed.
The Bundesbank cut the repo rate by three basis points to 5.73 per cent  -
in line with market expectations following tighter money market conditions
recently.
The dollar closed in London at DM1.7151 against the D-Mark from DM1.7071 on
Tuesday. Sterling rose slightly against the US currency to finish at Dollars
1.4678 from Dollars 1.4638. It was also higher against the D-Mark, ending
nearly two pfennigs up at DM2.5173 from DM2.4987. The dollar finished New
York trading at DM1.7150.
Elsewhere in Europe the D-Mark was generally firmer after a range-bound
trading session. The Belgian franc was barely changed after the central bank
lowered rates by 10 basis points to 5.95 per cent.
The Italian lira weakened following signs of dissension among the Freedom
Alliance coalition which won last week's election.
The Washington Post story quoted Fed officials as saying that rates would
not be moved until markets had stabilised and the impact of the fall in
share prices and rise in long-term interest rates had been assessed.
Although higher US rates - nobody is suggesting they will fall - should be
dollar positive, the market appears to have reasoned that interest rate
stability will also favour the dollar as it will calm US equity and bond
markets, encouraging capital inflows.
Mr David Cocker, currency analyst at Chemical Bank, said the improved
performance of the dollar and sterling - a reversal of last week's move -
indicated a possible 'return to looking at fundamentals rather than looking
at inflation'.
Analysts, however, questioned the durability of these moves, saying they
depended on a sustained recovery in the stock and bond markets which was by
no means assured.
Mr Mark Geddes, treasury analyst at Midland Global Markets, said he remained
negative on sterling in particular, which had 'risen on the dollar's
coat-tails more than anything else'. He added that it was 'difficult to find
anything that might go right either on the political or the economic side
for sterling'.
However, Mr Tony Norfield, UK treasury economist at ABN-AMRO, said there
were other factors supporting sterling. These include a shrinking negative
interest differential, versus the D-Mark, and a reasonable yield premium on
sterling bonds over D-Mark bonds.
Mr Norfield added that these premia should attract capital inflows. He said
econometric estimates also suggested that the pound was fairly valued 'in
the mid-DM2.50s'.
Short sterling futures also continued their recovery, the June contract
finishing three basis points firmer at 94.50. The December future was 12
basis points up at 94.03. The Bank of England, meanwhile, put Pounds 592m
into the discount market, compared to a forecast shortage of Pounds 750m.
German call money remained fairly tight after the Bundesbank surprised the
market by withdrawing a net DM1.8bn from the banking system yesterday. Rates
were in a fairly wide range from 5.85 per cent to 6.05 per cent, slightly up
from Tuesday's 5.80/6.00 per cent. Opinion seems to favour rates moving
higher.
There was little movement in the futures market, the June Euromark contract
ending three basis points off at 94.54.
The recent woes of the Turkish lira continued yesterday, the currency
falling by 25 per cent against the US currency to trade at TL40,000 per
dollar, after Tuesday's close of TL32,000, before recovering slightly to
TL39,500.
The central bank set its official dollar rate at TL39,933, up from TL32,053
on Tuesday. The bank, which effectively devalued its official dollar rate by
28 per cent on Tuesday, calculates the rate as the average dollar offer of
10 banks on the interbank market at 1200 GMT.
The lira was weakened by falls in overnight money rates, at 90 per cent
against 120 per cent when trading opened. Analysts said that now that the
bank had decided to devalue, it was predictable that speculators would try
to drive the currency lower.
In Portugal, the escudo stabilised as the central bank persisted with its
policy of high interest rates. The currency finished at Es101.3 against the
D-Mark, up from Es101.8. The bank again injected funds into the money market
at 13 per cent and 14 per cent, compared to a previous rate of 10 per cent.
Mr Miguel Beleza, governor of the Bank of Portugal, told TSF radio that he
believed his strategy would allow key lending rates - such as banks' prime
rates - to continue falling.
The Belgian franc finished at BFr20.60 against the D-Mark from BFr20.61
before the trimming of rates. Analysts said Belgium had sufficient margin
over Germany to cut rates.
</TEXT>
