<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Hungarian land law infuriates
the business community
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS DENTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUDAPEST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A new land law passed yesterday by the Budapest parliament severely limits
foreign investment in Hungarian agriculture, one of the country's
traditionally strong sectors.
The act, although it does not affect existing holdings, bans new purchases
of land by foreign individuals and companies. It allows non-Hungarian
investors to lease no more than 500 hectares and then only for 10 years in
general.
The business community has reacted furiously to the new legislation.
'Foreign investment in the agricultural field is dead as a dodo,' said Mr
Adam Batthyany, head of Batthyany Securities and one of the largest private
landowners.
Officials in the agriculture ministry have also been critical of the
government's policy and included the limits on foreign land ownership under
duress.
An infusion of foreign capital and know-how had been widely seen as one way
to restore Hungarian agriculture to its former health. Hungary was the
eastern bloc's largest agricultural exporter but drought, loss of markets
and confusion over property rights caused output to fall 17 per cent in 1992
and a further 5 per cent last year.
Foreign purchases of land are, however, unpopular among a rural constituency
whose support is crucial to the conservative coalition's chances at next
month's elections and political calculations have proved decisive.
The discriminatory elements of the land act would be incompatible with
Hungarian membership of the European Union, for which Budapest formally
applied just last week.
The government said that the measures would apply only to the interim period
leading up to EU accession and until Hungarian land prices, currently a
fraction of western rates, reach 'realistic' levels.
Nevertheless, Hungary's policy is in general to harmonise domestic
legislation with EU directives in advance of membership and the land act
breaks with that practice.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
