<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / Government Bonds: Treasuries stage recovery in quiet trading
session
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY and ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US Treasuries recovered from early weakness yesterday in a quiet,
technically-driven session following Tuesday's powerful rally.
Late in the session, the benchmark 30-year government bond was  1/32 lower
at 87 27/32 , with the yield rising to 7.249 per cent. On the short end, the
two-year note was  1/32 better at 99 15/32 , to yield 5.394 per cent.
An uneasy calm descended as the session opened. Bonds showed modest gains in
early activity, as dealers followed through on the previous day's buying
spree, which propelled prices higher and pushed down yields after a
fortnight of relentless selling pressure.
By mid-morning, the market's efforts to adjust to its turbulent ride began
to take a toll. The early activity petered out, and the longer end of the
maturity range slipped into negative territory.
The downward drift followed a report in the Washington Post that the Federal
Reserve would wait until the financial markets steadied before raising
interest rates for a third time.
Near mid-day, the long bond suddenly dropped by nearly a point, but when a
broad sell-off failed to materialise, prices crept back to near their
opening levels.
In view of the market's volatility, the afternoon recovery was encouraging.
Traders were also pleased that prices held up after news of strong March
sales by US motor vehicle manufacturers, which suggested the possibility of
mounting inflationary pressures.
UK gilts opened firmer yesterday, encouraged by the overnight gains in US
Treasuries and a firmer pound. However, they fell back in the afternoon in
tandem with a weaker opening in the US.
The June contract of the long gilt future on Liffe went as high as 108 31/32
, but lost most of the day's gains by the late afternoon when it fell to the
day's low of 107 5/8 . It then picked up to 107 13/16 for a gain on the day
of just  3/32 .
Dealers said there was still no evidence that the buyers' strike was over in
the gilts market, despite the improvement in market sentiment since the long
Easter weekend. Indeed, one dealer reported that multi-currency funds were
selling gilts in favour of US Treasuries.
The release yesterday of stronger-than-expected money supply data for March,
which could indicate that retail sales were healthy last month, did not have
a great influence on the market.
The February data showed that UK institutions were net sellers of gilts for
the second month running to the tune of Pounds 338bn but that overseas
investors made net purchases of Pounds 1.5bn, the highest monthly figure
since August.
In addition, the figures indicated that the Bank of England gave only
limited support to the gilts market in February, with unofficial purchases
of up to Pounds 250m.
German bunds failed to make significant gains after the Bundesbank cut its
repo rate by three basis points to 5.73 per cent, in line with market
expectations, since the cut was effectively neutralised by a unexpected net
drain of DM1.8bn from the banking system.
The market had expected the Bundesbank to add a net DM2bn to DM4bn, so the
net drain pushed call money to around 6.15 per cent from around 5.80 per
cent.
The June contract of the Bund future on Liffe traded between a high of 97.36
and a low of 96.86 during the day and in the late afternoon it was quoted at
96.97, up 0.13 point on the day.
Italian government bonds remained volatile yesterday following the
announcement late on Tuesday that Mr Silvio Berlusconi had suspended talks
on the formation of a new government. Dealers said that investors were still
wary of committing themselves to the market until the political situation
improved.
The June contract of the Italian government bond future on Liffe traded
between a high of 113 and a low of 111.95 during the day. By the late
afternoon, it stood at 112.20, down 0.65 point on the day.
French government bonds ended off the day's highs ahead of today's auction
of OATs. The Treasury has said it will sell between FFr18bn and FFr20bn OATs
due April 2004, February 2004 and October 2025. The Bank of France's
monetary policy council also meets today, but dealers said that a cut in the
5.90 per cent intervention rate was unlikely.
The June contract of the notional 10-year French government bond future on
the Matif came off the day's best level of 123.92 to trade at 123.78 in the
late afternoon, down 0.12 point on the day.
</TEXT>
