FT  07 APR 94 / International Company News: GE acts to quell earnings fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
General Electric, the US conglomerate, said its earnings during the first
quarter of the year were 'at the high end of analysts' estimates', which it
said ranged from Dollars 1.45 to Dollars 1.50 a share.
The announcement marked an attempt by the industrial giant to scotch rumours
that its financial services businesses, which have been one of the main
engine of profits growth in recent periods, had suffered from rising US
interest rates.
In particular, market speculation centred on possible losses at Kidder
Peabody, the group's Wall Street brokerage house.
The concerns hit GE's share price during the day, pushing it down Dollars 2
1/4 at one stage to Dollars 96 5/8 . The shares staged a partial recovery
later to close at Dollars 97 5/8 .
In a statement, GE said that first-quarter earnings at both Kidder and GE
Capital Services, its financial services unit, would be 'excellent'. Dennis
Dammerman, the group's senior vice president in charge of finance, also said
that GE continues to expect record earnings for 1994 as a whole.
Kidder has had a patchy record in recent years and has been consistently
less profitable than its main competitors, leading to frequent speculation
that GE was looking to sell the business. Last year, though, operating
profits jumped to Dollars 439m from Dollars 300m the year before.
</TEXT>
