<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / International Company News: SE-Banken sells Swiss unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Skandinaviska Enskilda Banken, the leading Swedish commercial bank, has
announced the sale of Banque Scandinave en Suisse (BSS) for more than SKr2bn
(Dollars 250m). The buyer is the Sandoz Family Foundation of Lausanne.
SE-Banken declined to reveal precise terms for the deal, but said it would
have a 'significant positive' effect on earnings and a 'limited positive
impact' on its capital ratios.
BSS, a private Swiss bank specialising in fund and asset management, made a
SFr22m (Dollars 15.2m) profit last year and had total assets of SFr1.3bn as
at December 31 1993.
Mr Lars Isacsson, SE-Banken chief financial officer, said the sale was part
of the group's programme to concentrate on core activities. Earlier this
year the bank sold three subsidiaries within the Finans-Skandic group to GE
Capital as part of the strategy.
Mr Isacsson said SE-Banken intended to remain involved in fund and asset
management, but the emphasis would be on the Nordic area. 'Banque Scandinave
en Suisse developed a less Scandinavian flavour,' he stated, adding that its
importance to the group had diminished as European integration had
progressed. The bank intends to retain a private bank in Luxembourg to serve
international clients.
SE-Banken has owned a stake in BSS since 1964 when the operation was set up
in partnership with other Scandinavian banks. At the start of this year it
held 79 per cent of the bank before buying the outstanding shares from the
Northern Trust Corp of the US a month ago.
The Sandoz Family Foundation was set up in 1964 to maintain a 10 per cent
voting stake in Sandoz, the Swiss pharmaceuticals group.
</TEXT>
