<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / Smash-up delay on 'information super-highway': The
implications of two abandoned US telecommunications deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
With two juggernauts lying smashed at its side, the road to America's
'information super-highway' is looking increasingly bumpy.
On Tuesday, Southwestern Bell, the large Texas-based local
telecommunications group, announced that it was abandoning a plan to invest
Dollars 1.6bn for a 40 per cent stake in the cable television operations of
Cox Enterprises, a private media group.
Just six weeks ago Bell Atlantic, the Philadelphia-based phone group, and
Tele-Communications Inc (TCI), the largest US cable company, said they were
calling off a Dollars 22bn merger which Mr Raymond Smith, Bell Atlantic's
chairman, had once hailed as 'a model for communications companies in the
next century'.
The idea was that large telecoms and cable companies - which are potential
rivals in developing the information superhighway, a network offering
interactive multi-media entertainment and services - would do better to form
partnerships to pool their respective expertise. Cable companies are good at
providing entertainment services, while telephone companies have much
greater expertise at routing two-way communications traffic.
The collapse of the deals suggest that the introduction of multi-media
services will proceed more slowly than its most visionary proponents have
been suggesting and will not involve many full-blown mergers between
telephone companies and cable networks.
That said, America's leading phone and cable companies remain committed to
pouring billions of dollars into the development of an information
superhighway.
Both Bell Atlantic and Southwestern Bell have blamed the unravelling of
their deals on the Federal Communications Commission, the government agency
which oversees the communications sector, and on 1992 legislation which
ordered tighter regulation of cable TV prices after public criticism of
escalating rates charged by these essentially monopolistic companies.
In February, the FCC, under its new chairman, Mr Reed Hundt (a Clinton
administration appointee) ordered cable companies to cut by 7 per cent the
charges to consumers for a basic package of television channels. Bell
Atlantic and Southwestern Bell say the resulting reduction in cable
companies' cashflow undermines the financial assumptions on which their
deals were based.
Rate re-regulation has certainly increased financial uncertainty in the
cable industry, and diminished the immediate financial attractions of the
sector to the local telephone companies, which are themselves heavily
regulated and want to get into less controlled businesses.
However, analysts suspect that there is more to the collapse of the two
deals than can be laid at the FCC's door. Certainly, in the case of Bell
Atlantic/TCI, sharp differences in culture between the staid telephone
company and the free-wheeling cable operator appear to have played a role,
as well as Wall Street anxiety over the cost of the deal to Bell Atlantic.
If the information superhighway offers telephone companies as glittering a
financial future as industry leaders claim, should not they be willing to
ride out a short-term dip in cable cashflow?
The problem is that no one knows just how profitable, or when, multi-media
services will prove for the companies that provide them. It is far from
certain that consumers will actually want the services, ranging from movies
on demand to inter-active home shopping and computer games.
These factors suggest that while telephone companies will continue to press
ahead with capital investment in multi-media networks of their own, they
will proceed more gingerly with involvement in the cable industry, making
either small acquisitions in areas where they do not offer a phone service,
or joint ventures. One such route has been pioneered by Southwestern Bell,
which in January became the first regional phone company to buy a cable
system outright, paying Dollars 650m for two systems in the suburbs of
Washington DC, It where the number of homes taking a cable service is high.
Another route was pioneered last year by US West, the Denver-based phone
company, which spent Dollars 2.5bn on a 23 per cent stake in Time Warner's
cable TV and entertainment business.
Time Warner is planning to roll out a much-vaunted multi-media field trial
to 4,000 homes in Florida, but the launch date has been postponed from this
month to the autumn because of technical difficulties - a delay which raises
additional questions about the speed at which the information highway will
be built.
</TEXT>
