<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / Small businesses set to benefit in wide review of company
law
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Wide-ranging reform of company law aimed at helping the growth of small
businesses was signalled yesterday by Mr Neil Hamilton, the corporate
affairs minister.
Simplification of the 1985 Companies Act and the creation of a new corporate
organisation along the lines of an incorporated partnership are two ideas to
be considered by a Law Commission review, he said.
The review, announced yesterday, follows a Department of Trade and Industry
working party set up to study possible reforms of company law.
Part of the government's deregulation policy, the action is seen by
ministers as a means of removing obstacles to the growth of small businesses
into medium-sized companies better able to compete, particularly in the
European single market, and to provide increased employ-ment.
The DTI stressed, however, that the review should be seen as a necessary
updating of current legislation rather than dramatic root and branch reform.
An incorporated partnership might dispense with some existing concepts of
company law such as the distinction between shareholders and directors while
retaining other features such as separate legal responsibility and limited
liability.
The simplification of the Companies Act might allow companies to opt out of
some of its provisions. The protection provided for creditors and others
would not be diminished, Mr Hamilton said.
The commission will also look at reform of laws on legally binding corporate
documents like contracts and loan agreements.
The DTI considers there are still fundamental problems with the law
regarding such documents, such as conflicting and inconsistent statutory
provisions. It is expected that a consultation paper will be issued by the
commission on this subject in 1995.
The announcements were welcomed yesterday by the Federation of Small
Businesses. A spokesman said: 'A move towards incorporated partnerships
would be particularly important. It would help bridge the gap between
partnerships and companies which is currently a serious weakness in
Britain's industrial structure. At the moment, this gap means we are losing
out in our trade with the rest of Europe.'
The commission will identify specific areas needing attention. It will now
begin consultation to pinpoint the main problems facing small businesses
before making firm proposals.
The commission is expected to report to ministers by July. A DTI spokesman
said legislation would not follow immediately as recommendations would then
have to be studied fully.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
