<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / Arts: Lorca's life - Theatre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ST GEORGE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As the excellent Spanish Arts Festival continues in London, the Lilian
Baylis Theatre is staging a life of the poet and dramatist Federico Garcia
Lorca (1898-1936). This one-man show is written and performed by Trader
Faulkner; its closeness to Lorca's life alone makes exhilarating theatre;
but its greatest strength is the fine flamenco dance and music.
Lorca lived life on his emotions. His poems and plays, particularly the
1930s' Earth Trilogy of Bodas de sangre, Yerma and La casa de Bernada Alba
are rooted in the Andalusian earth. Few graduates in Maritime Law - Lorca's
degree at Granada University - can have been so attached to dry land. Lorca
duly evokes the bright streets and the dark interiors of Granada, the
passion of flamenco and the sadness of Cante Hondo, the Deep Song of the
Andalusian gypsies. This play makes Lorca's plays more understandable, his
poems less aloof. And, through Lorca's poems, it looks west towards new
writing in Spanish.
Lorca moves at an uneven pace; there is no plot and little sequence. It
tracks Lorca's sad, passionate life from leaving Granada in 1919 for Madrid,
his studies and friendships there with Luis Bunuel, Salvador Dali and Manuel
de Falla, his travels to New York and South America, and his return to
Granada where he was shot by the Fascists on August 19, 1936. Everywhere he
went he lived the painful life of a man on the verge of reinventing himself.
He was passionately in love with Dali. As a homosexual, he was often abused
as 'maricon' (queer) or 'perro' (dog), a nasty joke which inspired Bunuel's
Chien Andalou.
The play delivers all this, and sets Lorca's poems to music and dance,
flickering in and out of Spanish and English. Each scene is punctuated by
the flamenco dance and music which give the play its visceral quality. The
language - both Spanish and English - is sensual and visual, using Lorca's
own poems. There is a wonderful bullfight based on the death of Lorca's
friend Ignacio Sanchez Mejias the matador - A las Cinco de la Tarde. There
are sexually evocative love poems, stark pictures of rural Andalusia, and a
loose-limbed South American sequence where the stern rhythms of Granada meet
the New World.
The piece is superbly acted and sung. Trader Faulkner as Lorca, with the
excellent Tito Heredia (guitar), Liana Vargas (dance) and Luz Elena Caicedo
(songs) produce an ensemble performance of top quality. Faulkner himself
manages the bilingual feat of memory, the intricacies of flamenco steps, and
maintains the intensity of Lorca's life.
Lilian Baylis Theatre (071 278 8916) until April 23.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
