<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / Arts: La Gran Scena pays tribute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In case anyone still does not know who they are, La Gran Scena is a group of
American males whose speciality is presenting opera snippets in drag. Such a
bald description fails to do justice to the affection that has gone into
their portrayals of composite prime donne: a bouffant hairstyle here, a shy
protestation of unworthiness there. Detailed knowledge, too - the cooing
pianissimo whitening into the curlew mew of Madame X, the gallantly
heaved-out top register of Dame Y. The effect is less brash, even less
outrageously camp, than might be expected. These men obviously love their
opera. It's no surprise that their fans include Leontyne Price and Joan
Sutherland.
Above all, they love their dive. The pervasive image is that of the 1960s,
when Sutherland, Tebaldi and Bumbry were at their imperious height,
high-piled coiffeurs as much part of the uniform as the codified hierarchic
display of a mandarin's robes. But Ira Siff, the company's founder and chief
writer, has kept up with the times. One of the highlights of the new
programme is a tribute to such exponents of the new post-modern
deconstructionist school of opera production as 'Peter Sellout' (no prizes
for guessing who): the last act trio from Der Rosenkavalier set in a New
Jersey shopping mall, replete with surtitles for those who loathe them, sung
by Marsh-Lynn (a sleek matron returning from a barmitzvah), Octavian
(jiggling to his walkman in his 'I Love Older Women' T-shirt: Philip Koch,
impeccably in character as a woman playing a man) and a blonde hop-head
Sophie.
The programme's humour veers from pantomime-dame clumping via hoary Coarse
Acting jokes to the wickedly observant. Keith Jurosko's 105-year-old prima
donna quavering through Home Sweet Home evokes those crackly old
dinner-plate 78s and is oddly touching.
Johnny Maldonado's mezzo is unnervingly convincing, though it is not true
that Covent Garden has cast him as Amneris in their forthcoming Aida. The
company also includes Mirella Frenzi, the tenor Mario Costa-Plenti and such
distinguished understudies as Anna Turnover-Somehow, Batleen Cattle and Mo
Guiseppe Monopoli. And Ira Siff, the company's only begetter, triumphs in
the last act of La Traviata, which sums up the show's ambiguities under its
layers of artifice on artificiality: part parody, part homage, part shadow
of mortality falling across brittle, painted things.
Bloomsbury Theatre until April 13.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
