<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
So far Carlton TV, which took the London weekday ITV contract from Thames in
the government's demented auction scheme, has achieved an unimpressive
record. Today they could begin to change that with Class Act a drama series
starring Joanna Lumley as a wronged aristocrat whose husband disappears,
leaving her with a prison sentence. She teams up with a female Australian
burglar and a doubtful journalist, and their adventures form the backbone of
the one-hour series.
It is good to see Lumley reaping the benefits of 'AbFab', and encouraging to
find that Class Act is produced by Verity Lambert. But what about the
writer? On the one hand Michael Aitkens wrote 'Waiting For God' which I rate
higher than 'One Foot In The Grave' (in its writing, anyway). On the other
hand his most recent offering is 'Honey For Tea' which has been something
like a disaster. We shall see (9.00 ITV).
The last in Dawn French's series of comedy dramas, Murder Most Horrid II,
finds our heroine playing a would-be torch singer in the gangland setting of
London's east end in the 1960s (9.00 BBC2).
