<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / Employment 'skills gap' widens further
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The 'skills gap' in Britain is widening again, says the Department of
Employment's latest analysis of skill shortages.
The gap - defined as the difference between the skills of existing employees
and those needed to meet business objectives - was reported by 17 per cent
of employers in 1993. The proportion compared with only 14 per cent in 1991,
adds the report written by Mr Ian Dale of the department's statistical
services division.
But employers do not appear to have immediate skill-related recruitment
problems. Only 6 per cent reported hard-to-fill vacancies when asked in the
middle of last year, compared with 22 per cent in 1990.
An increasing number of hard-to-fill vacancies are in low paid, low-skill
jobs. In 1990, 40 per cent of such vacancies were defined as high-skill, but
the figure is now 28 per cent.
The main industry with recruitment difficulty is hotels and catering. In
this sector21 per cent of employers reported problems.
Others worst affected by the 'skills gap' were textiles and electrical and
electronic engineering.
Last year, 10 categories accounted for three-quarters of all hard-to-fill
vacancies: catering trade workers, textiles and garments workers, nurses and
related health professions, sales representatives, engineers and
technologists, transportation operatives, miscellaneous sales staff, sales
assistants and checkout operators, clerks and cashiers, and teachers.
Only 5 per cent of manufacturing companies expected a lack of skilled labour
to limit output in the early months of this year. This compared with a peak
of 28 per cent in 1988.
But the Association of British Chambers of Commerce has reported that in the
fourth quarter of last year 42 per cent of manufacturing companies had
recruitment difficulties - the highest level since 1990 when the proportion
peaked at 73 per cent.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
