<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / Plans to break up N Yorks attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Trade and industry associations representing more than 600 companies in
North Yorkshire have written to the prime minister opposing the local
government review.
The Local Government Commission wants to break up North Yorkshire and create
smaller, unitary authorities. The name 'riding' would be revived for some of
them.
Yortek, which represents engineering and other manufacturers, has joined
with Yorkshire Pantry - a food and beverage industry trade body  - and the
Vale of York Small Business Association to support the status quo.
In their letter, Mr Howard Chadwick, Mr Bill Taylor and Mr Ian Traynor - the
organisations' respective chairmen - tell Mr Major: 'North Yorkshire has
served us extremely well over the last 20 years. These proposals will lead
to the break-up of professional and cost-effective services.
'The proposals are not generally supported by local businessmen and are
based on predictions of financial savings which are marginal and so prone to
error that we could certainly not recommend an investment decision on such a
basis,' they add.
The commission's plans are 'ill-founded, grossly unpopular and totally
inappropriate'. Asking for discussions 'at the highest possible level', the
chairmen claim the views of business have been ignored.
</TEXT>
