<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / Concession offered on school tests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
External marking for national curriculum tests in England and Wales could be
introduced next year, Baroness Blatch, the education minister, announced
yesterday.
Her announcement was greeted with applause from the annual conference in
Blackpool of the NASUWT teaching union, which last year took the lead in
enforcing a boycott of the tests supposed to be taken by all seven-year-olds
and 14-year-olds.
It was the most cordial reception the union has given a Tory education
minister for more than a decade and signalled a big shift in its position
since cuts to the tests were announced in January by Sir Ron Dearing, the
government's chief curriculum adviser.
It also deepened the split between NASUWT and the National Union of
Teachers, which will continue its boycott of all tests.
Mr Nigel de Gruchy, NASUWT general secretary, called on Lady Blatch to have
the tests marked externally this year.
He dismissed as 'codswallop' claims by NUT leaders that external marking
would reduce teachers to 'technician' status and undermine their
professionalism.
Lady Blatch said she would consult next term on possible changes for the
1995 tests and also gave support for Wandsworth Borough Council's decision
to use supply teachers as external markers.
She said: 'It is open to schools to draw on supply cover as you yourselves
have suggested, and where schools do make such arrangements that is to be
welcomed.'
But Mr de Gruchy said: 'Surely if you think tests are so important for
standards, it is not beyond the wit of this government to organise external
markers and make sure that the tests take place this summer.'
Without external markers, the NUT boycott will probably prevent tests in
several thousand schools.
However, there were warning notes for ministers from the third teachers'
union, the traditionally moderate Association of Teachers and Lecturers,
which yesterday opened its conference in Bournemouth.
The ATL last night took a card vote on a motion condemning its executive for
not holding a second ballot on the boycott. The result is expected this
morning.
Mr Peter Smith, ALT general secretary, said the government was 'on
probation' this year. If Sir Ron's exercise proved 'cosmetic or expedient',
he could not rule out a boycott next year.
</TEXT>
