<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / Railtrack meets council today over threat to fees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Talks will be held today between Strathclyde Passenger Transport Authority,
which operates the largest suburban rail network outside London, and
Railtrack in an attempt to resolve a threat to the financing of suburban
railways.
Strathclyde announced on Tuesday that it would be withholding its Pounds 33m
subsidy for this year to ScotRail, which operates the railway network around
Glasgow, until it had more information on the increase in fees it must pay
for the use of track.
The authority calculates that the increase in track access fees announced by
Railtrack in February will increase the subsidy needed from Pounds 33m to
Pounds 95m. Strathclyde wants more details of how this sum is arrived at,
said Mr Charles Gordon, vice-chairman of Strathclyde Regional Council's
transport committee.
Strathclyde is concerned that it would be unable to justify the payment to
its auditors until it has a breakdown of the numbers involved. Railtrack
said it would be happy to provide Strathclyde with the details at today's
meeting.
Seven passenger transport authorities in Britain met Mr Roger Freeman,
transport minister, last week, and appeared to accept a government assurance
that higher track access charges would be matched by a higher subsidy, the
Department of Transport said.
</TEXT>
