<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / NUM is told S Wales mine will close
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Coal plans to close Tower colliery, its last deep mine in south
Wales, on April 15, executives told union officials yesterday.
It said the pit would be maintained until it is offered for sale in parallel
with the privatisation of other mines later in the year.
A pithead meeting will be held on Saturday at which Tower colliery's 200
miners will decide whether to appeal against closure through the industry's
review procedure. This could delay closure by up to nine months, but a vote
to fight the shutdown is unlikely.
British Coal said that all contracted and anticipated demand for coal mined
in south Wales could be supplied from other existing sources.
Mr Tyrone O'Sullivan, secretary of the Tower NUM lodge, accused British Coal
of closing the pit 'purely to get us out of the way for privatisation'. He
said British Coal was offering Pounds 7,000 per man on top of redundancy
payments - the extra payment would be withdrawn if the men decided to go
ahead with the review procedure.
South-east Northumberland faces a total loss of 2,000 jobs during 1994 and
the three following years on top of up to 1,000 jobs shed last year, says a
report to be considered by county councillors today.
Research by PA Cambridge Economic Consultants for the county council says
recent closure and redundancy announcements in the county, especially in its
industrialised south-east corner, have already put it on course to fulfil
the highest predictions of coal-related job losses in the coming years.
About half the 2,000 forecast job losses have happened in the past few
months with the sudden closure of Northumberland's last pit, Ellington.
</TEXT>
