<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / Minister admits threat to pension growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Millions of holders of personal pensions may be losing up to seven months'
growth for their savings each year because of delays in transferring their
National Insurance contributions to their personal pensions.
This aspect of personal pensions is the latest to put the government under
pressure. The possibility of delays was confirmed in a letter from Mr
William Hague, the pensions minister, to Mr John Denham, Labour MP for
Southampton Itchen.
The time-lag arises because the payments from the Department of Social
Security can be made only after an employer has submitted the end-of-year
PAYE tax return. The return is needed so that the minimum contribution to be
made to the personal pension can be calculated. Mr Denham called on the
government to look at where the delays were occurring. If that was in the
late submission of tax returns, more pressure should be brought on employers
to deal with them promptly.
'The exact figure for each person will obviously depend on the performance
of their own pension fund,' Mr Denham said. 'But year in, year out, seven
months' worth of growth lost could make a huge difference to the pension
that is paid out.'
No information is collected centrally on the normal length of delays or the
sums which might be foregone in pension growth. However, some Pounds 3.5bn
in contracted-out pension contributions was paid into private pensions for
4m people in 1991-92, the last year for which figures were available.
Mr Hague's letter said payments were normally made between May and October
following the end of the tax year.
The Contributions Agency, an executive arm of the DSS, said the longest
period for processing payments would normally be no more than six weeks
after it had received the tax return. The agency has a target of processing
98 per cent of all such cases by the end of December following the tax year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
