FT  07 APR 94 / Blunkett attacks spending policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr David Blunkett, shadow health secretary, yesterday called for more
spending on public services, in a speech at odds with his party leadership's
view that shadow cabinet members should avoid making expenditure
commitments.
He told public-sector trade unionists in Blackpool that the Labour party
offered 'care before accountancy', and problems could not be solved by
'taking them out of public spending'. The 'stupid belief' that privatisation
and de-regulation were the only way to deal with difficult issues had to be
set aside once and for all.
Mr Blunkett accused the government of creating an 'off-balance-sheet'
approach in an attempt to offload forthcoming dilemmas on to the backs of
individuals.
Labour's 'critical task' was to restore commitment and confidence to public
services and investment in them.
He said provision of more money for improving patient care could be partly
financed by avoiding the bureaucratic and costly administration which had
become endemic in the health service as a result of the government's
market-oriented changes.
