<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / Squeeze makes the smaller Peps squeak: The price war that
has broken out in the Pounds 5bn-a-year tax shelter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The recent decision by merchant bank Barings to stop taking applications for
personal equity plans shows the extent of competition in the Pep market.
An aggressive price war backed by heavy advertising to promote 'name
awareness' has raised the stakes for smaller Pep providers. And some
companies complain that their distribution costs are increasing as
independent financial advisers demand annual renewal commissions on top of
initial commissions.
Peps, which began in 1987, are popular tax shelters for private investors.
Up to Pounds 6,000 a year can be invested free of capital gains or income
tax in a general plan and a further Pounds 3,000 in single-company Peps. The
general plan market has grown steadily from Pounds 1.6bn in the 1990-91 tax
year to Pounds 3.1bn in 1992-93 and is estimated to be a record Pounds 5bn
for the tax year just ended.
Baring Global Fund Managers, the bank's asset managing arm, is a relatively
minor player - Peps represent Pounds 15m of its Pounds 3bn in managed assets
 -and the company is putting its Pep business on hold pending a review of
its retail operations.
Mr Nick Wells, product development manager, said: 'What stuck out like a
sore thumb is that our Pep business is tiny compared to our institutional
business.' He added: 'We do not want to discount nor do we want to put up
standard charges.'
Discounting is widespread. In 1992, Fidelity introduced tapered exit charges
on its Peps allowing it to cut the initial charge to 2 per cent from the
industry average of 5 per cent to 6 per cent. It continued to pay 3 per cent
commission to intermediaries.
This year, M&amp;G, the largest Pep provider, went further by abolishing the
initial charge on its Managed Income Fund Pep and introducing withdrawal
charges. Ms Rachel Medill, head of corporate communications, said: 'We are
subsidising the managed income Pep, but we hope that it will be profitable
over five years.'
Nor is Barings the only company to feel the pressure. Mr Martin Harrison,
managing director of GT unit managers said: 'We've felt the impact of the
M&amp;G move on our own sales. The price war is unfortunate because more
companies will move out. We'll be left with the giants and the niche
players.' Chase de Vere Investments, publisher of an annual Pep guide,
estimates 20 per cent of companies take 80 per cent of Pep money.
The main costs of administering a Pep are sending out six monthly valuations
to customers and recovering tax deductions on dividends from the Inland
Revenue. Mr Michael Short, managing director of Premier Administration,
said: 'You would need to take in at least Pounds 10m to Pounds 20m in a unit
trust for it to break even, and the amount would be much higher for a Pep.'
To survive on the low margins, companies are relying on generating
sufficient volume to make profits and on the annual management charge, which
has been edging up to 1.5 per cent.
Ms Judy Delaforce, product development manager at Fidelity, thinks the
Barings move could point the way for many more Pep providers. She said: 'A
lot of small players will not be able to afford to stay in the Pep market.'
</TEXT>
